@article{Canham1990,
abstract = {Light regimes beneath closed canopies and tree-fall gaps are compared for five temperate and tropical forests using fish-eye photography of intact forest canopies ad a model for calculating light penetration through idealized gaps. Beneath intact canopies, analysis of canopy photographs indicate that sunflects potentially contribute 37-68{\%} of seasonal total photosythetically active radiation. In all of the forests, potential sunfleck duration is brief (4-6 min), but the frequency distributions of potential sunfleck duration vary because of differeces in canopy geometry and recent disturbance history. Aalysis of the photographs reveals that incidence angles for photosynthetically active radiation beneath closed canopies are not generally vertical for any of the forests, but there was considerable variation both among and within sites in the contribution of overhead versus low-angle lighting. Calculations of light penetration through idealized single-tree gaps in old grouth Douglas-fir - hemlock forests indicate that such gaps have little effect on understory light regimes because of the high ration of canopy height to gap diameter. However, single-tree gaps in the other four forest types produce significant overall increases in understory light levels. There is also significant spatial variation in season total radiation in and around single-tree gaps. Our results demonstrate that there can be signifiicant penetration of light into the understory adjacent to the gap, particularly in high latitudes. As gap size increases, both the mean and the range of light levels within the gap increases, but even in large gaps (ca. 100 m2) the potential duration of direct sunlight is generally brief ({\textless} 4 h). The major differences in gap light regimes of the five forests are largely a gunction of canopy height and latitude. The effects of latitude should also result in differences in gap light regimes across the geographic range of individual forest types.},
