@article{Veblen1992,
abstract = {1. A plant species may be termed persistent if its population does$\backslash$nnot become extinct during a given time period in a given area, or,$\backslash$nif it does, it recolonizes the area within the time span required$\backslash$nfor one turnover of its population. Plant communities in which all$\backslash$nthe common plant species are persistent may be judged to be in compositional$\backslash$nequilibrium.$\backslash$n$\backslash$n2. A critical consideration in the assessment of compositional equilibrium$\backslash$nis the spatial scale at which it is investigated. In a vegetation$\backslash$nmosaic consisting of small patches of different species composition,$\backslash$nindividual patches are often not in compositional equilibrium, even$\backslash$nthough equilibrium may exist at the spatial scale of the entire mosaic.$\backslash$n$\backslash$n3. The patch dynamics perspective emphasizes the importance of periodic$\backslash$ndisturbance in creating opportunities for establishment of new individuals$\backslash$nor growth of previously suppressed individuals by releasing the resources$\backslash$nutilized by the former dominants of the site. Investigation at a$\backslash$nwide range of spatial scales of the temporal and spatial characteristics$\backslash$nof disturbances and plant population responses to disturbances is$\backslash$nessential to an understanding of the regeneration dynamics and$\backslash$n$\backslash$nvegetation patterns in any landscape.$\backslash$n$\backslash$n4. Recognition of compositional equilibrium in contrast to successional$\backslash$ntrends is methodologically difficult for long-lived organisms such$\backslash$nas trees. The surest method, but also the least practical , requiresrepeated$\backslash$ncensuses over multi-year periods. Faster but less certain methods$\backslash$ninclude stand structural analysis and computation of transition probabilities.$\backslash$nBoth methods must be applied with great caution due to the unlikelihood$\backslash$nof obtaining all the data required (e.g. many trees cannot be precisely$\backslash$naged) and the difficulty, without long-term studies, of verifying$\backslash$nassumptions underlying these techniques.$\backslash$n$\backslash$n5. In forest stands at or near compositional equilibrium, species$\backslash$npersistence often involves a combination of resource partitioning$\backslash$nand nonequilibrium mechanisms of coexistence. For many tree species,$\backslash$ndifferences in resource needs and mode of acquiring resources may$\backslash$nbe manifested only during the early stages in their life histories,$\backslash$nas emphasized by the regeneration niche concept. Fine-scale disturbance$\backslash$nin the form of treefalls, however, also favours coexistence by truncating$\backslash$n$\backslash$nprocesses of competitive exclusion and by contributing to the spatial$\backslash$nand temporal heterogeneity of resource availability.$\backslash$n$\backslash$n6. The regeneration niches of tree species may be differentiated in$\backslash$nrelation to the heterogeneity of resource availability associated$\backslash$nwith: (1) gap size, shape and orientation; (2) seasonality and periodicity$\backslash$nof gap creation; (3) the micro-environmental influences of the canopy$\backslash$ntree which previously occupied the gap; ( 4) the nature of substrates$\backslash$nwithin gaps; (5) abundance and composition of gap-occupying understorey$\backslash$nplants; or (6) presence of animals and micro-organisms within gaps.$\backslash$nWhile differences in regeneration niches are often critical to the$\backslash$ncoexistence of tree species, differences among mature trees in their$\backslash$ninfluences on microsites and in their mortality patterns also contribute$\backslash$nsignificantly to their coexistence.},
